Ate here after a busy day visiting Indianapolis. Myself and my business associates had an "ok" meal. The Kettle chip appetizer was sub par, expected warm fresh chips but got cold oily bland chips instead, no salt or pepper. The chili aoli dipping sauce was bland and had no body. Tasted like olive oil that had been emulsified (only olive oil has more flavor).  I had it replaced with the "sweet chili gochujang" sauce , much better sauce, nice spice and balanced sweetness and good body that would cling to the chip.  My associate got the "chips and salsa" appetizer.... Please don't waste your money, the chips were borderline stale, and not salted at all, so very bland, the queso was WAY too thick and as it cooled from it's luke warm state, after arrival at the table, it only got thicker. It also included something that looked like pico de gallo but tasted like a mixture of cucumbers, tomatoes, and canned white northern beans. No salt, no black pepper, no onion, no chilis, and NO FLAVOR.  For my entree I got a simple Caesar salad with a medium rare yellow fin tuna. It was ok. Too much powdered parmesan cheese, which was very salty. I would have preferred more of the flaked parmesan which is nuttier and a much better compliment to the tuna. The dressing was also too salty and lacked depth of flavor. The two croutons would have benefited from some light butter or spice or something. Tasted like crunchy stale bread and not a crouton. I personally would've liked them thicker and larger too, (close to the size of a medium size baget cut on the bias). My associate got the pork chops, I don't think they were the best because he left a third of them on the plate. If not for the Server, this place would have gotten 3 stars.
Great atmosphere and location within walking distance of downtown. The food was just okay on this visit - chicken was very dry. A good selection of drinks, and the dessert was very good.

Kinda meh!  Sauce on the "known for" meatloaf tasted like a red gravy for pasta.  That ruined the meatloaf because all I could think of at that point was spaghetti and meatballs.  Meatloaf was interesting, but fell apart, so it was like eating loose ground meat.  So, basically, I had a dinner of Bolognese sauce without the pasta.  Nice atmosphere and decent service.  Just feel disappointed.

Since we were staying at the Holiday Express right across the way, we thought this would be a good place to unwind and get a quick bite. I can sum up our experience in one word: unimpressed.  We sat outside and the waitress comes over, doesn't Introduce herself and looks both my wife and I kind of sideways. Perhaps she sensed a gay vibe and was none too happy to serve us. I really didn’t care but I felt something less than professional from her.  I asked if they had “Belvedere” and she shook her head dismissively. I then asked if they had Ketel One and, again a dismissive shake of the head. At this point I wished I didn’t have to pry it of her. “Well what do you have?” I asked. She said Grey Goose. “Ok, I will take that.”  She brings the drink and it’s extremely watered down (God when will I learn NOT to order vodka at a restaurant? They always water it down.  I switched my drink out for a scotch but I went inside and asked the bartender myself. Our waitress saw what I was doing and didn’t acknowledge my problem or anything.  For food, I ordered two appetizers: the ahi tuna and the pretzels. The pretzels were awesome! Fresh and hot.  The ahi tuna, ok but i’ve had much better at a sushi restaurant. My wife ordered a Cesar salad with chicken. For $11 you would expect a fresh salad with more than 2 dried, flavorless pieces of toast. The chicken was passable but I could have made much better at home with one of those salad kits.  Overall, we were extremely disappointed. Now we are waiting for the bill. I wonder if they will try to charge us for the watered down drink?

The server didn't get my husband's drink correct...not complicated...vodka water lemon...never lemon. Never a "your welcome", tuna app was just ok...we both ordered the 7oz filet. One was over done...the second under done. Veggies were supposed to be asparagus and potatoes. We received 4 very thin asparagus and the smallest serving of potatoes...the presentation was terrible. I would like to say this is more of a 3.5 star review. To start we had the kettle chip with garlic aioli and roasted red pepper dipping sauces. The chips themselves were very good, however, the sauces were good but not great. They did not pack a lot of flavor. I had to try pretty hard to taste any garlic in the aioli. I ordered the blackened rib tips. On paper these looked amazing. In reality, they were good. That's it. Some were dry and chewy while others were perfect. The bloody Mary was very good as was our service by Scott. Despite the lackluster first visit, I really want to like this place. It has a great location, great atmosphere and sitting on the outdoor balcony looks like a good time. For these reasons I think we will definitely give Tavern on South another shot.

We recently hosted a Rehearsal Party for our son's wedding.  Steve and his team at Tavern on South were wonderful to work with ... from planning the menu, to set up and of course the food.  We hosted as a luncheon buffet with three entrees.  Each was excellent with rave reviews from the group.  Desserts and sides were excellent.  The staff was friendly and accommodating for our group of 40+ including children and an infant.  The free parking is a bonus -- but, the food and customer service will bring you back.  If we ever have occasion to host a large party in Indy again, Tavern on South will be our first choice.  Our previous lunch and dinner experiences have been excellent too.
